  <entry>
    <id>https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/soy-and-mirin-tuna-on-soba-noodles</id>
    <title>Soy &amp; mirin tuna on soba noodles</title>
    <updated>2026-04-18T17:19:04.101445+00:00</updated>
    <content type="html">&lt;h1 style="text-align:center;font-family:sans-serif;"&gt;Soy &amp; mirin tuna on soba noodles&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;img src="https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/soy-and-mirin-tuna-on-soba-noodles.webp" style="text-align:center;"/&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;p style="font-family:sans-serif;&gt;Soba means 'buckwheat' in Japenese and there are two types of soba noodles - the normal dark brown noodle with the natural colour of buckwheat and the green-coloured 'green tea' soba. You can use either, but the green tea version looks very pretty and gives a fresher, lighter taste to the dish.&lt;/p&gt;</content>
    <link href="https://www.strangerfoods.org/recipes/soy-and-mirin-tuna-on-soba-noodles"/>
    <published>2026-03-30T00:00:00+00:00</published>
    <media:group>
      <media:thumbnail url="https://www.strangerfoods.org/images/soy-and-mirin-tuna-on-soba-noodles.webp" height="288" width="512" time="0"/>
